<br>
My <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> personal</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> definition of indirect in this instance was obviously based upon what is traditionally considered a Magician role on the way to level 60 - dealing <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> direct</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> damage. In fgct its the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> direct</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> component of this term that I probably derived my on-the-spot personal direct / indirect contribution definition from.<br>
<br>
Direct - deal damage directly to the target.<br>
Indirect - do other stuff to make the fight win. Contribute mana, debuffs, healing, etc etc etc.<br>
<br>
Im sorry if I confused you there. Fact is though that in the situation Ive described (lend), and in most higher-end encounters vs. boss mobs, Magicians go from providing a direct damage dealing role to an indirect contribution.<br>
<br>
Yup, clerics are important, can't kill lendy without them. Sorry if you inferred that this meant &quot;lesser&quot;, &quot;worthless&quot; or &quot;not really very important for the success of the venture&quot;. Mod rodding is pretty useful, and is clearly a contribution to the kill, but it doesn't mean that after 60 levels of shaking norrath with pets and spells I am particularly hapy with a total paradigm shift to being an indierct contributor. <p><B><A HREF="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=26251">Hogfather</A></b><P>
